{"id":14880748,"mediaExerciseId":"472fbbf0-b12e-4ce2-8594-bdb892fed78e","exerciseName":"9","chapterName":"2","chapterTitle":"Financial Statements, Taxes, and Cash Flow","groupId":612264,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":42,"solutions":[{"id":5977333,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires will let us discuss why cash flows to creditors and shareholders may be negative.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/325b7a7fad614013dfd7ee925d7cc8af/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/325b7a7fad614013dfd7ee925d7cc8af/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Cash flows to creditors represents all cash from net borrowings and interests paid. Its formula is shown as follows:\n\n$$\\begin {array}{lrr}\n\\text{Interest paid}&&\\$\\hspace{15pt}\\text{xx}\\\\\n\\text{Less: Net new borrowing}&&\\underline{\\hspace{20pt}\\text{xx}}\\\\\n\\text{Cash flow from creditors}&&\\underline{\\underline{\\$\\hspace{10pt}\\text{XX}}}\\\\\n\\end{array}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":214,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/a18f148ad67507227545c9f9d2d9d8a7/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":109,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/a18f148ad67507227545c9f9d2d9d8a7/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"When interest paid to creditors exceeds the new net borrowings, the result will be a positive cash flow from creditors. If interest payments are more significant than money received from additional borrowings, its value will be negative.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/81fb5a9c51dcdd7cf46df9837603d5fb/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/81fb5a9c51dcdd7cf46df9837603d5fb/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"All cash related to business owners will fall under cash flows to stockholders.  Presented below is the proforma for its computation.\n\n$$\\begin {array}{lrr}\n\\text{Dividends paid}&&\\$\\hspace{15pt}\\text{xx}\\\\\n\\text{Less: Net new equity raised}&&\\underline{\\hspace{20pt}\\text{xx}}\\\\\n\\text{Cash flow from stockholders}&&\\underline{\\underline{\\$\\hspace{10pt}\\text{XX}}}\\\\\n\\end{array}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":214,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/4dea491f90d08e8434d7896fb767ca14/lateximg_large.png","width":994},"regular":{"height":109,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/4dea491f90d08e8434d7896fb767ca14/lateximg.png","width":496}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"When dividends paid to stockholders are higher than the new net equity raised, it will result in a positive cash flow. On the other hand, it will result in a negative balance when cash receipts from shares exceed all dividend payments.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/ca1fb1c7a37915c0ba6edafd70a3a61c/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/ca1fb1c7a37915c0ba6edafd70a3a61c/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Any entity must hold enough cash to fund its daily operations, pay its liabilities, and distribute income to shareholders. Understanding the cash flows from liabilities and equity would help maintain the business liquidity - by having a sufficient cash level.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/ed69c3bcd4926255cc3cd4298d4db60a/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/e51f0985b147e079f0ef1f624d8850bd/ed69c3bcd4926255cc3cd4298d4db60a/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"6409d869-e09e-4fa0-aac3-5804186a8104","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":6},{"id":5899773,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to explain the possibility of negative cash flow to shareholders and creditor. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"First, let's define the cash flow to shareholders and the cash flow to creditors. \n\n**Cash flow to shareholders** is the amount of money that passes to shareholders in the form of dividends after new equity is deducted. While **cash flow to creditors** is the amount of money paid to the debt holders during an accounting period.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":61,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/e766dadce75afe7ac60a632be81e14bc/ac69464ad24f68b4636ecbbe8bc8e5f5/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":32,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/e766dadce75afe7ac60a632be81e14bc/ac69464ad24f68b4636ecbbe8bc8e5f5/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**Negative cash flow to shareholders** occurs when a company raises more money from selling shares than it pays out in dividends in a given period. \n\nMeanwhile, **negative cash flow to creditors** occurs when a company borrows more from creditors than it pays in interest and principal.Â ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":179,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/e766dadce75afe7ac60a632be81e14bc/4091c452f10ebe853148214bece19873/lateximg_large.png","width":1050},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/e766dadce75afe7ac60a632be81e14bc/4091c452f10ebe853148214bece19873/lateximg.png","width":526}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"6f62ab5b-6c5a-446b-8958-9a8c5c418896","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880749,"exerciseName":"10","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"19ee8364-760b-489b-ac16-d492be8a4a08","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanati